Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This data set contains information about 10,000+ movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue.

Columns¶

id The unique ID for each movie

int (5-417859)

imdb_id The unique ID used by IMDB

str, ex. tt0369610

popularity A score generated on lifetime popularity

float (0.000065-32.985763)

budget Budget allocated for the movie

int (0-425,000,000)

revenue Revenue generated by the movie's release

int (0-2,781,506,000)

original_title Original title of the movie

str, ex. Jurassic World

cast Actors and actresses featured in movie separated by "|"

[str], ex. Chris Pratt|Bryce Dallas|...

homepage Movie Website

str, ex. http://www.jurassicworld.com/

director Movie director

str, ex. Colin Treverrow

tagline Short tagline for the movie

str, ex. The park is open.

keywords Keywords to search for movie separated by "|"

[str], ex. monster|dna|...

overview Summary of the movie

str

runtime Length of movie in minutes

int (0, 900)

genres Movie genres separated by "|"

[str], ex. Action|Adventure|...

production_companies List of Movie's production companies separated by "|"

[str], ex. Universal Studios|Amblin Entertainment|...

release_date Movie's release date

Date MM/DD/YY

vote_count Number of votes for movie

int (10, 9,767)

vote_average Average movie rating from votes

float (1.5-9.2)

release_year Year of release date

int (1960-2015)

budget_adj Adjusted budget

int (0.000000e+00, 4.250000e+08)

revenue_adj Adjusted revenue

int (0.000000e+00, 2.827124e+09)

Question for Analysis¶

  1. When did movie homepages become popular?
  2. Is there a average votes rating that is an indicator if a movie has a higher chance of being profitable?
  3. What are the most common genres?

Functions¶

In [2]:
def display_lineplot(data, x, y, xlabel, ylabel, title, legend=True):
    """Display a seaborn lineplot

    Arguments:
    ----------
    data - Pandas dataframe to display
    x - x axis variable
    y - y axis variable
    xlabel - label for x axis
    ylabel - label for y axis
    title - title of the plot
    legend - bool if should display legend (default = False)
    """
    if x is not None and y is not None:
        sns.lineplot(data=data, x=x, y=y, legend=legend)
    elif x is None and y is None:
        sns.lineplot(data, legend=legend)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title);

Assessing the Data Findings¶

  1. All listed movies have at least vote
  2. Need to make a column with profit (revenue_adj - budget_adj)
  3. There is 1 duplicated row
  4. There are 4,701 records missing budget and revenue data
  5. One missing field that could be helpful is the movie rating.

Data Cleaning¶

In order to clean the data, the following steps will be taken:

  1. Remove the duplicated row.
  2. Remove the movies with missing revenue and budget data since using the mean would not be accurate. Approximately 40% of the movies are missing this data. Had it been a lower number and the ranges been smaller, I would have used the mean to fill in the missing values.
  3. Create a column for profit_adj.
  4. Remove unused columns.
  5. Split out Genres. TODO

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Tip: Now that you've trimmed and cleaned your data, you're ready to move on to exploration. Compute statistics and create visualizations with the goal of addressing the research questions that you posed in the Introduction section. You should compute the relevant statistics throughout the analysis when an inference is made about the data. Note that at least two or more kinds of plots should be created as part of the exploration, and you must compare and show trends in the varied visualizations. Remember to utilize the visualizations that the pandas library already has available.

Tip: Investigate the stated question(s) from multiple angles. It is recommended that you be systematic with your approach. Look at one variable at a time, and then follow it up by looking at relationships between variables. You should explore at least three variables in relation to the primary question. This can be an exploratory relationship between three variables of interest, or looking at how two independent variables relate to a single dependent variable of interest. Lastly, you should perform both single-variable (1d) and multiple-variable (2d) explorations.

Conclusions¶

Original Questions

Question 1: What year did homepages for movies start to become popular?¶

It is difficult to determine the exact year homepages for movies became popular. The percentage of movies with a homepage by year graph proves movies released prior to the public availablity of the internet had homepages created post-release. However, movies released 2007 or later are likely to have a homepage. Therefore, movies released 2007 and later are more likely to have a homepage. Interestingly, movies released between 2013 and 2014 had fewer homepages made. Further investigating didn't show a strong relationship between popularity and homepages. To investigate further, a machine learning model would be needed.

One limitation of the data was not knowing if the homepages were created after the release of the movie. In order to fully answer the question, a field storing the creation date of the homepage would be needed.

Question 2: Is there a average votes rating that is an indicator if a movie has a higher chance of being profitable?¶

When a movie is released, there is about a 72% chance it will be profitable. The ratings appear to be an indicator if it will or will not be profitable. It appears if a movie is rated 5.25 or higher, it is at least 50% likely to be profitable. A movie rated 6.5+ has over an 82% chance of being profitable.

A limitation of this analysis is the missing budget and revenue data. There were many zero values that could improve the analysis.

Question 3: What are the msot common genres?¶

The top 3 most common genres are Drama, Comedy, and Thriller.
